title: For Sale:  Savage 110 Left Hand Premier Grade .243 Winchester LH Lefty L.H.
postcontent:
Savage 110 Premier Grade left hand bolt action rifle. Caliber is .243 Winchester.

Stock is French Walnut with Rosewood highlights. It has a rollover cheekpiece, and is hand checkered.

At the time this gun was made, it would have likely been one of the top end production rifles available. The only period ad I could find for the Premier Grade was from 1967, and retail price was $220, which would be $1567 today!

Overall gun is in very good shape. Some dents and dings in the stock as pictured, nothing major. Bluing on the barrel is immaculate, some slight wear on the receiver as pictured on the moving surfaces. The kind of wear you’d expect to see on a brand new rifle after a few days in the field. Bore is immaculate. I think you’d struggle to find one of these in better shape.

Factory installed rifle sights, and factory drilled and tapped for scope mounts or a peep sight.

Gun has been disassembled, parts ultrasonically cleaned (where possible, everything else was cleaned by hand), reoiled, and reassembled. This gun is ready to rock and roll.

If I’m reading the proofmarks on the barrel correctly, this gun was made in 1972.

I bought it thinking I wanted a larger caliber than the 22-250 I already had (which is also a left hand savage 110), but the more I thought about it, for 99% of what I’m ever going to do with a rifle, 22-250 is more than adequate, and 243 really is overkill for me.

title: For Sale:  For Sale : Lee Enfield Number 4 Mark 1
postcontent:
Lee Enfield Number 4 Mark 1

Markings -

No.4.Mk1 - model and mark . model number 4, mark 1

Seagull shaped V - stamp of acceptance. passed inspection. usually above factory and year mark, this stamp hit between the factory and year mark.

M 1943 - factory and year. M indicates the Maltby royal ordnance factory in Maltby, England. year 1943.

A G - serial number prefix. A G was the first prefix used early in 1943. A also indicates the gun was assembled using
some non-standard parts from contractors. This means it was hand crafted and unique, so it will most likely
have very little compatibility with standard rifles of the same model. G is a simple reference letter.

13480 - serial number. range of 10000-19999. This rifle was the 3,481st of 10,000 in the A G prefix group.

Approximation - This rifle was produced in February of 1943 at the Maltby royal ordnance factory. It was assembled by hand using the best parts available. The overall finish and appearance of the gun was secondary to the performance. It is one of a kind and shoots great. It may have been used in battle in 1943-1945.

All original and in great shape. $160 cash.

title: For Sale:  Kahr Arms CW 9 (9mm)
postcontent:
I have an almost new Kahr CW 9mm for sale.  This handgun has only 200 rounds through the barrel as recommended by the manufacturer for break in, and has spent most of the time in the box.  It is less than 2 years old.  Asking $325, and compared to prices in stores or on line shops it is a steal as you save tax.  I have all the paperwork and a concealed holster for the CW9

About the gun: The Kahr CW9 is a semi-automatic small-frame pistol chambered in 9mm. Kahr is one of the premier manufacturers of pistols and has lines for major calibers such as .45, .40, .380 and, of course, 9mm. The CW9 stand alone whereas others have a handful of sub-models. What makes it different is it’s larger than the other models.

Otherwise it has similar features including a locked-breech system where the backwards force is absorbed by the slide rather than the frame. The overall width is 0.90″ making it easier to conceal. It has a double-action only trigger that sets off the action with a longer pull. It doesn’t have a safety, but it’s less likely something other than a trigger finger will pull a double-action trigger all the way back. It also has a passive striker block, which is an internal safety that prevents the gun from accidentally discharging if dropped. And it comes with adjustable three-dot sights.  The frame is black, while the slide has a matte stainless finish.

The sights are the typical dot front, bar rear configuration found on other Kahr pistols.  The front sight is polymer and fixed onto the slide.  The rear slide is steel and dovetailed.  The rear steel sight allows the shooter to use the sight to rack the slide one handed when training for one hand reloads and malfunction clearing drills.

title: For Sale:  Yugoslavian Mauser Model M24/47 - One Beatiful Rifle!
postcontent:
The M24 series is a line of Mauser pattern bolt-action battle rifles produced for use by the Yugoslavian military. They are similar to the Czech vz. 24 rifle, featuring open sights, 8x57mm IS chambering, carbine-length barrels, hardwood stocks, and straight bolt handles. All M24 series weapons are designed to accept the M-24/48 pattern bayonet.

The first Mauser-pattern rifle produced in Yugoslavia was the M24. Its predecessor, the FN Model 1924 had been produced for the Yugoslav army by FN Herstal until the Ministry and FN signed a contract on the purchase of the license for production of rifles 7.9 mm M 24. Nearly all M24's were produced either before or during World War II, at the Kragujevac Arsenal plant. The M24 and Model 1924 are nearly identical.

M24 series rifles were used by the Royal Yugoslav Army and the Yugoslav Partisans during World War II. The final additions to the M24 family were the M24/47 and M24/52 rifles. Both were produced by reworking existing prewar Model 1924 rifles after World War II at the Zastava Arms (formally Kragujevac Arsenal) plant, which was at that time under the control of the postwar communist government. "47" and "52" indicate the beginning of the rebuild program for each respective model: 1947 for the M24/47 and 1952 for the M24/52. Minor cosmetic differences exist between the M24/47 and M24/52, but the rifles are nearly identical to one another and to their predecessors, the Model 1924 and M24.
